6, 2000, the anniversary of D-Day, at 529

00:03.085 --> 00:15.940
Helena, and getting ready to chat with Mr. Fred 
Nelson. Mr. Nelson, would you say a sentence or

00:16.541 --> 00:18.563
two? Let's check your mic. Well, it's nice to have 
you, and it's one of those things, like I said, I

00:20.245 --> 00:31.098
feel flattered, you know, that you want me to 
recount the days when I was a day in and out. All

00:31.118 --> 00:31.578
right, sir. Nice to see you now.

00:37.763 --> 00:44.632
Mr. Nelson, to begin with, please tell us about 
your growing up. Where were you born? Where did you

00:45.594 --> 00:47.817
go to school? What did your parents do for a living? 
How long had they lived there? Well, we have some in

00:54.366 --> 01:01.896
common that you may not know about or I may have told 
you before, but I grew up in Collin County. My

01:03.278 --> 01:05.020
parents were sharecropping people. And I grew up 
on a farm in a community called Lovejoy. That's

01:11.988 --> 01:16.013
where I went to school until the ninth grade. And in 
those days, high school ended in the 11th grade. So

01:22.322 --> 01:32.897
after finishing at Lovejoy, I then went to Boyd 
High in McKinney, Texas, where I was graduated in

01:22.322 --> 01:32.897
1930. And as you probably will recall, that the 
beginning of the Great Depression was my era. And I

01:43.170 --> 01:52.984
didn't particularly like farm work, so I went into 
the music business, having been talented at

01:43.170 --> 01:52.984
piano. We had little bands in high school. And from 
that situation there, from having become a

01:57.470 --> 02:06.242
musician, so to speak, I went on, and during the 
Depression, I made whatever living I could from

02:06.323 --> 02:14.835
playing around with different bands. So from 
there, out of McKinney, I left somewhere probably

02:16.658 --> 02:32.601
in the mid-30s and started out on the road with 
various musical organizations from somewhere

02:16.658 --> 02:32.601
maybe in the the area of the south to the east coast, 
and halfway to the west coast from time to time with

02:34.640 --> 02:45.695
the various types of bands.

02:48.358 --> 02:51.362
What were the names of some of the bands you played 
with? Well, one I can think of right offhand, we had

02:52.083 --> 03:02.217
our own bands, you know, and we organized, but we 
never did really have a name. until I'd say in the

03:02.635 --> 03:09.328
mid-30s, I went with a band out of Waco called the 
Joe Buzzy Band. B-U-Z-Z-E, Buzzy. And we toured

03:14.278 --> 03:19.649
Texas on one-night stands, et cetera, et cetera. 
And until about 1939, I got tired of that one night

03:25.028 --> 03:29.133
stand thing and traveling over the state of Texas. 
And so I left the organization and went to Fort

03:29.754 --> 03:35.641
Worth where my sister and her husband lived. And 
eventually I went into,

03:37.363 --> 03:49.197
let's see, I've forgotten what the name, as I think 
of it, general merchandising thing, you know.

03:52.949 --> 03:53.950
Let's see what was the name. I couldn't remember 
what the name was. You could probably remember the

03:56.292 --> 03:58.114
name. There was a big organization there in Fort 
Worth, and I worked. Leonard, was it Leonard

04:03.320 --> 04:04.961
Brothers? It was Dawes Crossford Street from 
Leonard's. You remember what? No, sir. I'll

04:09.566 --> 04:10.107
remember it. Anyway, I went into the clothing 
business, and so in 1940, I had a call from one of the

04:20.395 --> 04:31.913
musicians that I played in a band with around 
McKinney, and he wanted to know if I'd be

04:20.395 --> 04:31.913
interested in coming to A&M and playing piano in 
the Aggieland Orchestra. Well, having always

04:33.235 --> 04:40.446
wanted to go to A&M, I guess you could say I might 
have jumped at the chance. And as an aside, I also

04:41.506 --> 04:53.117
had a chance at the same time to go with, at the 
behest of another musician I worked with before,

04:41.506 --> 04:53.117
to go to Texas Tech. So I was considering going to 
Texas Tech and playing a band out there, or come to

04:54.058 --> 05:00.644
A&M. So like I say, having always aspired to be an 
Aggie, I chose to come to A&M, and I came here in

05:01.705 --> 05:09.572
1940. Let me back up a little bit about your 
parents.

05:16.595 --> 05:19.163
Do you have any idea how many acres they farmed? 
Yes, I think we had 140 some odd acres. And we farmed

05:22.715 --> 05:26.120
cotton, corn, oats. You know, and sometimes we 
tried wheat, but wheat didn't grow well in that

05:26.581 --> 05:30.827
part of the country. Which of those was the most 
profitable? Cotton? Cotton, probably so, yes.

05:37.437 --> 05:38.378
Where did y'all gin it? In McKinney.

05:42.244 --> 05:46.069
And was McKinney where you went to spend money, to 
shop? Yes, uh-huh. McKinney, we were southeast of

05:47.825 --> 05:53.872
McKinney about seven miles in a community called 
Lovejoy. Also a little Baptist church called

05:53.892 --> 05:59.579
Friendship where I was converted. And then there 
was a funeral situation, a cemetery at Forest

06:00.440 --> 06:05.886
Grove. And then between the two churches, Lovejoy 
was on the farm road out there. Now what were your

06:13.556 --> 06:15.638
duties on that farm? Well, I picked cotton, 
gathered corn, and the usual things. But I had two

06:22.535 --> 06:28.883
older brothers who did the plowing and managing 
the livestock and that type of thing. And you all

06:29.544 --> 06:32.167
plowed with mules, or did you have a tractor? With 
mules. Tractors were a novel thing in those days.

06:37.814 --> 06:41.519
And let's see, electricity, telephone? Well, we 
had a community telephone. but no electricity,

06:44.879 --> 06:55.389
you know, lamps, coal oil lamps, and eventually 
you got one of those gas things, you know, the air

06:44.879 --> 06:55.389
type thing. And where was your well, your water? We 
had two wells, one for the stock at the farm on the,

07:00.553 --> 07:14.346
you know, out around the barn area, and one near the 
house, both of which finally went beyond the

07:00.553 --> 07:14.346
depth, you know, water dropped off, you know. And 
so we started having to haul water in. And we, there

07:21.506 --> 07:27.674
was a creek near our place, near the community. Was 
that Spring Creek or East Fork of the, or Rowlett

07:27.934 --> 07:32.921
Creek? I believe it was probably East Fork. And 
let's see. There's a After our water level dropped

07:44.043 --> 07:58.659
below the level of our wells, there was a place down 
on this what they call Wilson Creek. It had a well on

07:59.860 --> 08:00.941
it. The water was practically to the top of the 
ground. The water level there was so, I guess it was

08:04.865 --> 08:10.371
feeding off that creek. So we used to haul, my dad 
had a, a big tank made and put it on the wagon and we'd

08:13.625 --> 08:21.916
go down there and draw water and haul it home and 
that's what we used. That's how we kept water at the

08:22.417 --> 08:25.061
house. And how did you get to school when you went 
into McKinney? My dad had a car and I had two sisters

08:31.550 --> 08:40.662
who were students at the time and one of my sisters

08:43.426 --> 08:51.273
McKinney and they had, I don't know what it was,

08:43.426 --> 08:51.273
to go to school. Oh, so you would go to town and spend 
the night in town? No, we'd drive, oh, I would drive

08:57.479 --> 09:09.771
the car, you know, and there was two or three guys

08:57.479 --> 09:09.771
from Lovejoy there that went to McKinney and 
really formed that, yeah. Where

09:10.696 --> 09:29.833
did you learn to play the piano? Well, I started 
sitting around... But

09:32.245 --> 09:48.764
the piano, when I was

09:32.245 --> 09:48.764
about

09:32.245 --> 09:48.764
six or seven years old, I guess I had a natural 
talent. And I just progressed from there. From

09:49.524 --> 09:51.767
every year, I seemed to maybe improve a little bit 
or learn a little bit of something. And I might say,

09:51.787 --> 09:57.213
I have often said that I started playing the piano 
when I was six. And I learned by myself. Although I

09:59.355 --> 10:01.678
had older sisters. So

10:02.047 --> 10:23.311
you didn't have any formal piano instruction? You 
didn't? You never had a teacher outside the

10:24.593 --> 10:27.696
family? Well, When

10:28.979 --> 10:50.916
I was about

10:28.979 --> 10:50.916
in, I guess, maybe the fourth or fifth grade, I had a 
teacher who taught me for about three months. But

10:50.936 --> 10:53.801
when the end of the school year, and when she came 
out of my camp, you know, and goes out there to

10:50.936 --> 10:53.801
teach. But when the school term ended, when I was 
having my lessons with her, Did you

10:56.080 --> 11:07.761
have a model? Who were you trying to play the piano 
like? No, I

11:11.572 --> 11:24.706
didn't have a, see, we didn't have a radio in that 
place. And I used to,

11:24.726 --> 11:33.055
did you ever hear a singing school? Well, we had a 
singing school. And every year, this band was also

11:34.176 --> 11:36.299
a community member, had a special community out of 
a songbook. So I used to make those things. I guess I

11:36.959 --> 11:38.541
might have been the one or two, if we haven't known 
over a few years. And I may have learned some things

11:38.892 --> 11:42.838
from doing that. So were you playing gospel music 
first? Yes. Church music? Yes. But we didn't have a

11:48.686 --> 11:56.077
radio, you know, so we didn't get the benefit of the 
programs that were sent out over the radio. And

11:56.097 --> 12:02.186
mainly I began to play songs in the songbook. And 
I've never learned to read music. Did

12:06.989 --> 12:17.683
you

12:06.989 --> 12:17.683
ever use any of the Stamps Quartet music? Oh, yes. 
There was another piano man in the community who

12:20.787 --> 12:30.239
specialized in the Stamps Quartet music. And I 
never tried to compete with him because I was more

12:30.259 --> 12:35.005
inclined to the popper music. level of music than 
otherwise. So when you finished high school, you

12:38.161 --> 12:43.767
worked a little, and then you went on the road. And 
about what year did you first go on the road? Let's

12:48.192 --> 12:48.933
see. I was 30. I was 18. And I have to kind of recount 
how far back I went on the road. I believe that my

12:59.846 --> 13:05.312
first introduction to the popular music that I 
learned was when Two friends of mine, one a country

13:05.917 --> 13:17.111
man and the other a intersex man, we used to get 
together and play. And I had little small bands and

13:17.131 --> 13:24.721
we appeared in a little dance hall, you know, there 
in McKinney for a while. Well, these two guys

13:24.741 --> 13:27.765
belonged to the National Choir. And one summer, at 
the county picnic, One of them, the trumpet man,

13:34.013 --> 13:42.693
approached me and said, how would you like to go to 
